GenomicHeatmaps Answers

Rockefeller University, Bioinformatics Resource Centre

https://rockefelleruniversity.github.io/

In this session we will review some CTCF ChIP-seq data from the Encode consortium datasets.

These include the replicated peak call for Lung, Brain and Kidney sample.

  • Kindey CTCF peakcalls - ENCFF784YSO

  • Lung CTCF peakcalls - ENCFF116ZIX

  • Heart CTCF peakcalls - ENCFF409RRE

  • Kindey CTCF BigWig - ENCFF193CUU

  • Lung CTCF BigWig - ENCFF633LEJ

  • Heart CTCF BigWig - ENCFF688LXO

beds <- dir(pattern="bed.gz")
bedsAsDF <- lapply(beds,read.delim,sep="\t",header=FALSE)
grangesOfBeds <- lapply(bedsAsDF,makeGRangesFromDataFrame,seqnames.field = "V1",start.field = "V2",end.field = "V3")
grangesListOfBeds <- GRangesList(grangesOfBeds)
nrSet <- resize(grangesListOfBeds,width = 1000,fix="center")
names(grangesListOfBeds) <- c("Lung","Heart","Kidney")

Exercise 2 - Create a vennDiagram of overlaps between Lung, heart and kidney peaks with out non-redundant set of peak.

nrSet <- reduce(unlist(grangesListOfBeds))
nrSet$Lung <- nrSet %over% grangesListOfBeds["Lung"]
nrSet$Heart <- nrSet %over% grangesListOfBeds["Heart"]
nrSet$Kidney <- nrSet %over% grangesListOfBeds["Kidney"]

require(limma)
## Loading required package: limma
## 
## Attaching package: 'limma'
## The following object is masked from 'package:BiocGenerics':
## 
##     plotMA
vennDiagram(mcols(nrSet))

Exercise 3 - Create BED files containing peaks unique to Lung, Heart and Liver as well as peaks common to all samples. Also save these to GRanges objects for later use.

export.bed(nrSet[nrSet$Lung & !nrSet$Heart & !nrSet$Kidney,],con="LungSpecific_CTCF.bed")
export.bed(nrSet[!nrSet$Lung & nrSet$Heart & !nrSet$Kidney,],con="HeartSpecific_CTCF.bed")
export.bed(nrSet[!nrSet$Lung & !nrSet$Heart & nrSet$Kidney,],con="KidneySpecific_CTCF.bed")
export.bed(nrSet[nrSet$Lung & nrSet$Heart & nrSet$Kidney,],con="Common_CTCF.bed")

LungSpecific <- nrSet[nrSet$Lung & !nrSet$Heart & !nrSet$Kidney,]
heartSpecific <- nrSet[!nrSet$Lung & nrSet$Heart & !nrSet$Kidney,]
kidneySpecific <- nrSet[!nrSet$Lung & !nrSet$Heart & nrSet$Kidney,]
common <- nrSet[nrSet$Lung & nrSet$Heart & nrSet$Kidney,]

Exercise 4 - Sample 2000 peaks from the non-reduced set of peaks and write to a new bed.

nrSet <- nrSet[sample(1:length(nrSet),2000),]
export.bed(nrSet,"nrCTCF.bed")

Exercise 5 Provide more sensible sample names and colour the heatmaps by tissue.

rownames(sampleData(ctcf_profile)) <- c("Kidney","Lung","Heart")
sampleData(ctcf_profile)$Tissue <- c("Kidney","Lung","Heart")
generateEnrichedHeatmap(ctcf_profile,color_by_sample_group = "Tissue")

Exercise 5 Provide more sensible sample names and colour the heatmaps by tissue.

ctcf_profile <- clusterRanges(ctcf_profile,kmeans_k = 6)
## K means clustering used.
## A column has been added to the range metadata with the column name 'cluster', and the 'rowGroupsInUse' has been set to this column.
generateEnrichedHeatmap(ctcf_profile,color_by_sample_group = "Tissue")

Exercise 6 Create a violin plot of signal in peaks across samples and clusters

toPlot <- summarize(ctcf_profile,output = "long",fun="rowSums",sampleData_columns_for_longPlot = "Tissue")
require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
ggplot(toPlot,aes(x=cluster,y=Signal,fill=Sample))+geom_boxplot()+scale_y_log10()

Exercise 7 Annotate the clusters using Rgreat and write annotated cluster 5 to a data.frame.

ctcf_profile <- annotateRanges_great(ctcf_profile,
                                              species = "mm10")

peakGRanges <- rowRanges(ctcf_profile)

toWrite <- as.data.frame(peakGRanges[peakGRanges$cluster == 5],row.names = NULL)

write.table(toWrite,file="Cluster5.txt",sep="\t",row.names = FALSE)

Exercise 12 Provide more sensible sample names and colour the heatmaps by tissue.

ctcf_profile <- groupBy(ctcf_profile,group = GRangesList(KidneySpecific,common))
generateEnrichedHeatmap(ctcf_profile)
